A very wide periodic slit contains a symmetric electrolyte. Its lower and upper walls have the same slowly varying separation $h(x)=h_0[1+\epsilon\cos(kx)]$, with $\epsilon\ll1$ and $kh_0\ll1$. Both walls carry the same patterned zeta potential $\zeta(x)=\zeta_0\cos(kx+\phi)$. A uniform electric field $\vec E_0$ is applied parallel to the mean plates; the Debye length is much smaller than $h_0$, surface conduction is negligible, and inertia is absent. There is no imposed pressure drop unless explicitly stated.

Find the mean volumetric flux per unit span. In particular: **(a)** state the reduced physical model and the wall slip law; **(b)** derive the exact lubrication identity for the longitudinal flux through any periodic channel with arbitrary slip $u_b(x),u_t(x)$; **(c)** evaluate the leading non-zero flux when $\vec E_0=E_0\hat x$, and find the pressure gradient that stalls it; **(d)** if the field is instead at angle $\alpha$ to the pattern wavevector, determine the full mean flux vector; **(e)** decide what happens in the apparently delicate case $\phi=\pi/2$, and explain why the answer is not obtained by keeping more algebraic terms.

```figure caption="The false attractor is visible: the wall slip has zero ordinary average, but it is phase-shifted relative to the hydraulic resistance of the corrugated slit."
