```answer type=expression part=a
\vec u_s(x)=-\frac{\varepsilon_m\zeta(x)}{\eta}\,\vec E_t,\qquad
0=-\nabla p+\eta\nabla^2\vec u,\qquad \nabla\cdot\vec u=0,
```

```answer type=expression part=b
q=\frac{\left\langle S(x)h(x)^{-2}\right\rangle-\bar p_x/(12\eta)}
{\left\langle h(x)^{-3}\right\rangle},\qquad
S(x)=\frac{u_b(x)+u_t(x)}{2}.
```

```answer type=expression part=c
\bar q_x=-\epsilon h_0 U_E\cos\phi+O(\epsilon^3),\qquad
U_E=-\frac{\varepsilon_m\zeta_0E_0}{\eta},
\qquad
\bar p_{x,\mathrm{stall}}=12\eta\left\langle S h^{-2}\right\rangle
=-\frac{12\eta\epsilon U_E\cos\phi}{h_0^2}+O(\epsilon^3).
```

```answer type=expression part=d
\vec{\bar q}=\epsilon h_0 U_E\cos\phi
\left[-\cos\alpha\,\hat k+\frac{1}{2}\sin\alpha\,\hat e_\perp\right]
+O(\epsilon^2),
\qquad U_E=-\frac{\varepsilon_m\zeta_0E_0}{\eta}.
```

```answer type=freeform part=e
For the single sinusoidal geometry and single sinusoidal charge pattern, $\phi=\pi/2$ gives exactly zero mean pumping by mirror-antisymmetry, not merely a smaller next-order pump. A nonzero result then requires breaking that symmetry, e.g. a second harmonic, unequal wall patterns, finite-Debye-layer corrections, or surface conduction.
```

`````solution
**Necessary Insight.** The mean slip is the wrong average. Longitudinal pumping is set by a resistance-weighted average because a periodic pressure field must build itself to keep the flux independent of $x$. The hidden invariant is not energy or momentum; it is the constant Stokes flux plus periodicity of pressure.

**False Attractor.** Since $\langle \zeta(x)\rangle=0$, the Helmholtz-Smoluchowski slip has zero ordinary average. Concluding $\bar q=0$ is tempting and wrong whenever the charge pattern is not symmetry-locked to the hydraulic resistance.

**(a)** With $\lambda_D\ll h_0$, $kh_0\ll1$, $\epsilon\ll1$, and negligible Dukhin number, the electric double layer is replaced by a tangential slip at each wall,
$$
\vec u_s(x)=-\frac{\varepsilon_m\zeta(x)}{\eta}\vec E_t .
\label{eq:slip}
$$
The bulk electrolyte is locally electroneutral and obeys Stokes flow. To leading lubrication order, longitudinal pressure varies only with $x$ while the gapwise velocity profile is parabolic plus the two wall slips.

**(b)** For the longitudinal component,
$$
\eta\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial z^2}=\bar p_x+\tilde p_x(x),
\qquad u(0)=u_b(x),\quad u(h)=u_t(x).
$$
Integrating across the gap gives the local flux
$$
q=-\frac{h^3p_x}{12\eta}+\frac{h}{2}\,[u_b+u_t].
\label{eq:localflux}
$$
Incompressibility makes $q$ independent of $x$. Let $S=(u_b+u_t)/2$ and average the rearranged form
$p_x=12\eta(hS-q)/h^3$. Periodicity with imposed mean gradient $\bar p_x=\langle p_x\rangle$ gives
$$
q=\frac{\left\langle S h^{-2}\right\rangle-\bar p_x/(12\eta)}
{\left\langle h^{-3}\right\rangle}.
\label{eq:weighted}
$$

**(c)** For $\vec E_0=E_0\hat x$,
$$
S(x)=U_E\cos(kx+\phi),\qquad U_E=-\frac{\varepsilon_m\zeta_0E_0}{\eta}.
$$
Using $h^{-2}=h_0^{-2}[1-2\epsilon\cos(kx)+O(\epsilon^2)]$ and
$\langle h^{-3}\rangle=h_0^{-3}[1+O(\epsilon^2)]$,
$$
\left\langle S h^{-2}\right\rangle
=-\frac{\epsilon U_E\cos\phi}{h_0^2}+O(\epsilon^3),
$$
so
$$
\boxed{\bar q_x=-\epsilon h_0U_E\cos\phi+O(\epsilon^3).}
$$
The pump is stalled by choosing $q=0$ in \ref{eq:weighted}:
$$
\boxed{\bar p_{x,\mathrm{stall}}=12\eta\left\langle Sh^{-2}\right\rangle
=-\frac{12\eta\epsilon U_E\cos\phi}{h_0^2}+O(\epsilon^3).}
$$

**(d)** Rotate coordinates so $\hat k$ is the direction of pattern variation and
$\hat e_\perp$ is the in-plane perpendicular direction. The slip vector is
$$
\vec S=U_E\cos(kX+\phi)(\cos\alpha\,\hat k+\sin\alpha\,\hat e_\perp).
$$
The longitudinal part is pressure-constrained and therefore uses the weighted average from
\ref{eq:weighted}. The transverse part has no transverse pressure gradient in a very wide channel;
its local flux is just $hS_\perp$. Hence
$$
\bar q_\parallel=-\epsilon h_0U_E\cos\phi\cos\alpha+O(\epsilon^2),
\qquad
\bar q_\perp=\left\langle hS_\perp\right\rangle
=\frac{1}{2}\epsilon h_0U_E\cos\phi\sin\alpha+O(\epsilon^2).
$$
Thus
$$
\boxed{\vec{\bar q}=\epsilon h_0U_E\cos\phi
\left[-\cos\alpha\,\hat k+\frac{1}{2}\sin\alpha\,\hat e_\perp\right]+O(\epsilon^2).}
$$
The vector answer is the self-check: rotating the electric field does not simply rotate the pump.

**(e)** At $\phi=\pi/2$, $S\propto-\sin(kx)$ while $h$ and every resistance factor generated by
the single sinusoidal channel are even functions of $\cos(kx)$. Therefore
$$
\left\langle \sin(kx)F(\cos kx)\right\rangle=0
$$
for any single-valued periodic function $F$. The pump is exactly zero within this model; it is not an
$O(\epsilon^2)$ effect waiting to be found. A nonzero flux requires a symmetry-breaking ingredient
outside the stated leading model: a second harmonic in $h$ or $\zeta$, different upper and lower
patterns, finite-Debye-layer fields, surface conduction, or inertia.
`````
